@Warren

So, I guess I should have addressed your implied question more directly.  Biased samples are not useless. Bias is usually an issue of degree, not biased vs. not.

You wonder, I think, if one of the biases is that the tougher the puzzle, the greater the percent of non-finishers, and are these non-finishers excluded from the sample times. I think the answer has to be “yes,” and so, as puzzle difficulty increases, the population from which the sample is chosen decreases. It is likely that this smaller population has an average solve time (for whatever day of the week) that is shorter than that for the sample from the larger population that provides Xwstats solve-time data points for “easier” puzzles.  On average, most of the time, for a big enough sample, on most days, when the sun isn’t in your eyes….

